  "prompt": "How do QR codes work?",
  "response": "QR codes, or Quick Response codes, are a type of two-dimensional barcode that can store information, which can be quickly accessed by a device such as a smartphone or a tablet with a camera. Here's how they work:\n\n1. **Structure**: A QR code consists of a grid of tiny squares, typically black on a white background, which can encode data in both horizontal and vertical dimensions. This allows them to hold more information than traditional barcodes.\n\n2. **Encoding Information**: The QR code can encode various types of data, such as URLs, text, contact information, or other data. The amount of information encoded typically determines the size and complexity of the QR code.\n\n3. **Error Correction**: QR codes use error-correction algorithms, notably Reed-Solomon error correction, which allows the code to be partially damaged or obscured and still be read correctly. This is one reason why QR codes can work even when degraded or partially covered.\n\n4. **Reading QR Codes**:\n   - **Scanning**: Devices use a camera to scan the QR code. The camera captures an image of the QR code, which is then analyzed by software.\n   - **Decoding**: The software decodes the pattern of the QR code, converting it back into the format of the encoded data (e.g., a URL, text).\n\n5. **Usability**: Once decoded, devices can perform actions based on the encoded data. For example, if the QR code contains a URL, the device might prompt the user to open the link in a web browser.\n\n6. **Application**: QR codes have a wide range of applications, including marketing (linking to promotional content), payments, ticketing, product labeling, and more. They are popular because of their ability to quickly convey information and ease of use.\n\nOverall, the blend of encoding capacity, error correction, and ease of use make QR codes a versatile tool for digital information exchange.",
